<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 24 Nov 2004
From: Stephen Page <swp@advet.com.au>
I think some clarification is needed concerning the posting headed "Ryegrass
Staggers". While I am not situated in South Australia and have only an
interest in plant toxicity, I am sure that the disease is ryegrass toxicity,
not ryegrass staggers. Importantly, this disease is associated with
ingestion of toxins (corynetoxins) present in _Lolium rigidum_ (annual
ryegrass) and not _L. perenne_ (perennial ryegrass).
The toxins of _L. rigidum_ have a seemingly miraculous origin, in that they
are produced by the bacterium _Rathayibacter toxicus_, which infects _L.
rigidum_ via its vector, the nematode _Anguina funesta_.
Thus, this is a plant toxicity quite distinct (phytologically,
toxicologically, clinically, and geographically) from that due to endophyte-
infected perennial ryegrass.
--
Stephen Page
Advanced Veterinary Therapeutics
Australia
<swp@advet.com.au>
