[3]
Date: 24 Nov 2004
From: Malcolm Anderson <malcolm.anderson@protherics.com.au>
The recent article titled "Ryegrass Staggers - Australia (South Australia)"
refers to a warning for annual ryegrass toxicity, (ARGT), rather than
ryegrass staggers caused by affected perennial ryegrass, as discussed. ARGT
is generally more severe causing greater stock losses, and is caused by
ryegrass infected with nematodes and certain _Corynebacterium_ species.
--
Dr. Malcolm Anderson, Veterinarian
South Australia
<malcolm.anderson@protherics.com.au>
[From the article we received, with limited clinical signs, it appeared to
be ryegrass staggers, not ARGT. Thanks to our many Australian readers who
wrote to alert us that the event involved Annual Ryegrass toxicity (ARGT)
instead of Ryegrass staggers. They are certainly different syndromes with
different causes and consequences. - Mod.TG]
